bug.short_desc: EMF4ATL does not resolve proxy EPackages - NPE on using uninitialised meta-models

long_desc.thetext:
EMF4ATL throws a NullPointerException when trying to use uninitialised EMF meta-models. This happens for Eclipse EMF-based plugins that provide a meta-model, such as UML2, IODT ontology tools (http://www.alphaworks.ibm.com/tech/semanticstk), HibernateMapping30 (http://ssel.vub.ac.be/viewcvs/viewcvs.py/hibernate-mapping-3.0/), etc.
The NPE is thrown when EMF4ATL tries to access the Resource of the EPackage, which turns out to be null.

(In reply to comment #0) > The NPE is thrown when EMF4ATL tries to access the Resource of the EPackage, > which turns out to be null.
It turns out the NPE is thrown on accessing the EPackage ("pack"), which is already null. This means the EMF package registry itself returns null for the given nsURI.
I'm currently testing a modification that postpones loading the extent. On the first call to getExtent(), the ASMEMFModel should try to load the extent again. The assumption here is that getExtent() is only called after loading a model that is an instance of this meta-model.

This bug is related to the way OSGI works in Eclipse: an Eclipe plugin is only loaded after the first access to one of it's classes. For EMF plugins, this means that a meta-model is not available in the EMF registry before the plugin is loaded. The EMF plugin is loaded once a model is actually loaded (class access). The startup code of the EMF plugin then registers the meta-model.
Patch with id 50827 of Bug # 155673 addresses this issue.
Integrated patch 50827 of Bug # 155673.

Created an attachment (id=55481) Patch that rolls back init() behaviour
> Integrated patch 50827 of Bug # 155673.
This patch used the local registry to register the "*" fallback resource factory. The fallback resource factory must however be registered against the global registry, otherwise _all_ global registrations will be overriden.
This patch also removes the call to addAllReferencedExtents() in the constructor, since the extent may not have been loaded yet.
Signed off by Dennis Wagelaar <dennis.wagelaar@vub.ac.be> to be published under the Eclipse Public License v.1.0 (http://www.eclipse.org/legal/epl-v10.html) or any later version.

bug.short_desc: [Viewers] Javadocs of ViewerLabel, ViewerLabelProvider, etc. should tell about null values

long_desc.thetext:
I20060830-1650
Javadocs of ViewerLabel, ViewerLabelProvider, ViewerCell, ViewerRow, etc. should tell which getters and setters (incl. constructors) accept/return null values.
The change for bug 155575 fixed just one instance of this issue: ViewerRow.setText(int, String) now accepts a null text. This should be documented in the Javadoc. Eclipse APIs usually don't accept or return null unless specified explicitly. All places where null is accepted/returned should be marked.
SWT Items disallow null for text, but allow null for images, fonts, and colors. ILabelProviders and companions allow null for text as well. The spot where null must be converted to "" should be well-defined.

(In reply to comment #0) > The spot where null > must be converted to "" should be well-defined.
Yes. Yes! We need better Javadoc for the new API.
Note that ILabelProvider and ITableLabelProvider both allow null values to be returned from getText(). We should be consistent with this rather than with SWT.
Tom could you please do the tooltip documentation - I am not sure I will get it right. The tooltip shift in particular need better javadoc.

Some other issues
ViewerLabelProvider#getTooltipStyle() needs a list of supported styles
I have updated all of the API for the new Viewer* classes that I wrote.

Tod, some changes in the javadoc of ViewerLabel look like breaking changes to me. I think the original assumption was that properties of the ViewerLabel are mapped 1:1 to properties of Labels.
E.g. Label#setFont(..) accepts null (which means the default font). Clients such as DecoratingLabelProvider.updateForDecorationReady(..) currently assume that they can set these properties to null; in fact, this is the only way to reset the font (or fg/bg colors) to the defaults.
So, I would suggest that setImage(..), setFont(..), setBackground(..), and setForeground(..) should accept null, and ViewerLabel(String, Image) should accept null at least for the image. Then, getImage() can also return null.
> Note that ILabelProvider and ITableLabelProvider both allow null values to be > returned from getText(). We should be consistent with this rather than with > SWT.
In 1.13, setText(..) does not accept null (explicitly) and ViewerLabel(String, Image) does not accept a null string (by the general Eclipse API rules). Either setText(..) and ViewerLabel(String, Image) should accept null strings, or getText() should be marked to never return null.

OK, here's what happened: person1 wrongly tagged the yet unchanged project with a "r321_*" tag. Person2 who did a real change in jdtoptions.txt probably saw the "r321_*" tag in the doc.map file and probably assumed that the version has already been increased to 3.2.1. I've fixed this now.

BTW, is it common practice to use a prefix, such as r321_ in the cvs tag to denote the branch? I think this normally should be avoided, since, obviously, its easy to break monotonicity. The standard recommendation is to add suffixes to a standard pattern.
I suspect its tempting to use prefixes, since that causes the version lists to be more conviently sorted (all similar tags "together" in the list). If that is the case, perhaps someone should request a feature enhancement to "sort by suffic"? Of course, if that's not the case ... then ... never mind :) Though, I would then like to know the reason.

On using prefixes vs. suffixes it should not really matter as long as the tagging is consistent for a particular release and the qualifiers correctly increment for each build of the release.
In this case I'm glad we caught this. If we had used suffixes then the org.eclipse.core.runtime.compatibility.registry bundle would have been released in 3.2.1 without its version being incremented properly to reflect a bug fix.

> On using prefixes vs. suffixes it should not really matter > as long as the tagging is consistent for a particular > release and the qualifiers correctly increment for each > build of the release.
That is not quite true. There have been some case where a feature's version number decreased from build to build even when all plugins' version numbers increased. The hash in qualifier of the feature's version number is taken from the qualifiers of its plugins, not from the full version number.
So if a plugin's version changes from, for example, 3.2.0.v20060801 to 3.2.1.r321_v20060901, and if the feature doesn't change in any way (which would be acceptable if the feature's third digit has already been increased since the last public release), then the feature's version number will decrease because its hash will decrease because the plugin's qualifier has decreased.
It is important that qualifiers always increase, regardless of what happens to the rest of the version number. After seeing many of the versioning problems in the 3.2.1 maintenance builds, I'm convinced that any release specific strings should be a suffix rather than a prefix.

re comment 15: I rather agree with Thomas. If the qualifier simply always must increase as per rule then we should simply go away from using the tags from the map file and let the build process generate a strictly increasing qualifier.

Does the feature hash only take into account the qualifier of the bundle versions and not the major.minor.micro parts?
To be honest I don't really care about using prefixes vs suffixes in the qualifier. But I do not like arbitrary restrictions like these.

One small request: when y'all figure this out, please write an article or a wizard or something on it because it's very confusing. (Of course one could argue that if it's that confusing maybe that's a "code smell" saying it should be simplified, but I'm not one to argue :))

long_desc.thetext: Problem is in NameMember.getTypeQualifiedName(char, boolean) which does not replace '$' with enclosingTypeSeparator for CLASS_FILE when indexOf('$') != -1...

I read again the documentation: /** * Returns the type-qualified name of this type, * including qualification for any enclosing types, * but not including package qualification. * For source types, this consists of the simple names of any enclosing types, * separated by enclosingTypeSeparator, followed by the * simple name of this type or the occurence count of this type if it is anonymous. * For binary types, this is the name of the class file without the ".class" suffix. * * For example: *
    *
  • the type qualified name of a class B defined as a member of a class A * using the '.' separator is "A.B"
    • *
  • the type qualified name of a class B defined as a member of a class A * using the '$' separator is "A$B"
    • *
  • the type qualified name of a binary type whose class file is A$B.class * using the '.' separator is "A$B"
    • *
  • the type qualified name of a binary type whose class file is A$B.class * using the '$' separator is "A$B"
    • *
  • the type qualified name of an anonymous binary type whose class file is A$1.class * using the '.' separator is "A$1"
    • *
* * This is a handle-only method. * * @param enclosingTypeSeparator the specified enclosing type separator * @return the type-qualified name of this type * @since 2.0 */ String getTypeQualifiedName(char enclosingTypeSeparator); The important point is: For binary types, this is the name of the class file without the ".class" suffix. ... *
  • the type qualified name of a binary type whose class file is A$B.class * using the '$' separator is "A$B"
    • So, we behave as documented => close as INVALID

Sorry, it's unbelievable, but I have to reopen this. From HEAD of IType: /** [..] * This is the name of the package, followed by '.', * followed by the type-qualified name using the * enclosingTypeSeparator. [..] *
  • the fully qualified name of a binary type whose class file is * x/y/A$B.class using the '.' separator is "x.y.A.B"
    • [..] */ String getFullyQualifiedName(char enclosingTypeSeparator); /** [..] * For binary types, this is the name of the class file without the ".class" suffix. [..] *
  • the type qualified name of a binary type whose class file is A$B.class * using the '.' separator is "A$B"
    • [..] */ String getTypeQualifiedName(char enclosingTypeSeparator); Javadoc of getTypeQualifiedName(char) was changed on 2005-12-14 from *
  • the type qualified name of a binary type whose class file is A$B.class * using the '.' separator is "A.B"
    • ==> The definition of #getFullyQualifiedName(char) is inconsistent: It says it uses the type-qualified name (which would result in "x.y.A$B"), but its example says "x.y.A.B". The implementation has probably been to return "x.y.A$B" for a long time, so I think the only action we can take now is to finally make the specification of #getFullyQualifiedName(char) match the implementation.

Created an attachment (id=80247) Fix
Fix with big warnings for the unexpected behavior of this API. We definitely need to make sure clients are made aware of the deficiencies of these methods.
Assign to Jerome who has the most valuable feedback on these API methods to decide what to do finally on this long standing issue... (see also bug 120640)

Can't we just fix the behavior to what the user expects here: No $, only '.'.
Even if it involves some dirty tricks in the implementation, but it would jut make all users life easier and less complicated. This issue is a source of reoccurring bugs. At the moment we in JDT UI have a utility method to wrap and fix getFullyQualifiedName.
The search engine was always capable of returning the full information (package name, enclosing type names, type name). We need this for correctness also there. See discussion in bug 182179 comment 7.

(In reply to comment #9) If there's no more information, the correct assumption would indeed be that A$B.class comes from a nested binary type
See JLS3 3.8: "The $ character should be used only in mechanically generated source code or, rarely, to access preexisting names on legacy systems." and JLS3 13.1: "The binary name of a member type consists of the binary name of its immediately enclosing type, followed by $, followed by the simple name of the member."

I've just plowed into this bug while looking into links in the Javadoc view. Ouch, ouch, ouch.
This is horrible. BinaryType is not fulfulling the specification of IType, and is behaving inconsistently with SourceType.
Please fix.
The concern about literal $ in class names seems silly - if the implementation can't resolve the ambiguity, then it can't resolve the ambiguity. But why not go for the option that will be correct 99.9% of the time, rather than the 0.1% option?

bug.short_desc: PathEntry framework should handle cygwin style paths on Windows

long_desc.thetext:
(Mailing list response from Mikhail Sennikovski)
I guess the logic of path conversion should reside in the Build System, but not in the Path Entry mechanism, since its the build system who knows what tool-chain is being used and how the tool-chain treats path information. The Path Entry in its turn should work with OS paths as it does now.
So I propose making the enhancement in the Build System if necessary to properly convert the include path information when calculating path entries.
Mikhail

(Another mailing list response from Mikhail Sennikovski)
My point is that the path translation should be performed in the Build System within the mechanism of path entry from option values calculation. See the org.eclipse.cdt.managedbuilder.internal.core.ManagedBuildInfo.getManagedBuildValues() method for more info.
When calculating the path entries, paths specified in the option values should be translated to OS path if necessary and Path entries containing regular OS paths should be created.
The tool definition may provide the path translation mechanism by specifying a java call-back. Build System would define a public implementation of such a call-back that would translate cygwin paths into windows paths, so windows tool definitions might reuse this call-back.

(Mailing list response from Doug Schaefer)
Yes, please be clear that using cygwin on Windows is optional. We have already caused a lot of confusion for poor mingw users (and there is a bug open on that) and I will be introducing the integration with the Windows SDK soon. On the other hand, another thing to think about is cross-compilers that run on cygwin which use cygpath. In the end, it really is the build tools that decide whether you are using cygwin or not.
All in all, cygwin is good and evil all at the same time. The JRE doesnt know about the cygwin file system. Maybe this is a use for the Eclipse File System to allow users to use cygwin paths while working in Eclipse, maybe not. Cygwin does kindly record its mappings in the Windows registry. But whatever we do, we cant mess up the use of native paths on Windows, and remember /usr/include is a valid native path which almost always has a different meaning with cygwin.

Created an attachment (id=49589) Proof-of-concept for proposed fix
Here is what I cooked up as a solution.
- In the build definitions schema I created an additional java attribute pathConverter for the toolchain and the tool. Path conversion can, in this manner, be specified globally for a toolchain or locally for an individual tool - Define a new interface IPathConverter which converts from a tool-specific string representation of a tool to an IPath. - The ITool interface is augmented by a getter method for the path converter. - The Tool implementation must be changed to read the pathConverter attribute from the configuration and create an instance of a pathConverter class. - The ToolReference implementation delegates getPathConverter() to it's parent. I am not very sure about this, just copied from other methods. - The ManagedBuildInfo.processPath() method seems just the right place to do the conversion. It will convert all library and include paths for a given tool - if the conversion is set.
To be done: The Tool must ask the Toolchain for a converter, if it does not have one itself.
Design considerations: - I must change (extend) the interface of ITool and IToolchain and this will break any implementations of third parties of which I am not aware. I did not, however, succeed to find any way to access the Tool's config information without extending the interface. - This really a clean solution of the problem: Only the toolchain vendor can know whether it's tools have a special way of handling paths.
Thanks, Mikhail, for your suggestion. I could not have found this place to implement the change on my own.
Please give opinions on my approach. Can we put this also into 3.1.1?

Created an attachment (id=49689) Complete fix
The fix is now complete from my perspective.
The tool will, if it does not have it's own converter specified, ask the toolchain for a converter which gives us the opportunity to specify converters globally for the toolchain and still override the setting for an individual tool
To be done: - Documentation changes - Fixing org.eclipse.cdt.managedbuilder.ui.tests issues with the interface changes - Providing unit tests for the new functionality
I think I'll be able to handle this by next Thurs. I'd love to see this fix in 3.1.1 - opinions etc? - Unit tests

Hi Norbert,
Your patch looks good. Here are some comments/suggestions:
1. Generally different options of one and the same tool might support different path formats, on the other hand an ISV might want to supply one converter implementation for different tools. That is why I propose the convertToPlatformLocation method to accept IOption and ITool as additional arguments, i.e. convertToPlatformLocation(String toolSpecificPath, IOption option, ITool tool); 2. As I understand the path converter mechanism is supposed to be used for tool options only. That is why it might be better to rename the IPathConverter interface to IOptionPathConverter. NOTE: there is a similar mechanism already available for environment paths (see org.eclipse.cdt.managedbuilder.core.IBuildPathResolver). We might also think about defining one common mechanism, although Im OK with keeping IOptionPathConverter and IBuildPathResolver mechanisms separate since IOptionPathConverter also includes the logic of dealing with path separators, while IOptionPathConverter should only translate paths. 3. Tool.getPathConverter(), Tool.java:2404 in case the tools parent is not a tool-chain, i.e. the tool belongs to resource configuration, I think the path converter still needs to be acquired from the tool-chain of the current configuration. 4. Copyright header is missing in the IPathConverter.java file. You might also want to check the revision date to be 2006 in other files you modified.
Thanks, Mikhail

This patch also fixes a minor issue with a test implementation of IToolChain in org.eclipse.cdt.managedbuilder.ui.tests.

Hi Norbert,
I haven't looked at the patch, but I have a couple of comments based upon the conversation.
> - The ToolReference implementation delegates getPathConverter() to it's parent. I am not very sure about this, just copied from other methods.
ToolReferences are part of the prior MBS object model (CDT 2.0?). They are not used by the current model, so your implementation is fine.
> - I must change (extend) the interface of ITool and IToolchain and this will break any implementations of third parties of which I am not aware. I did not, however, succeed to find any way to access the Tool's config information without extending the interface.
Interface breakage seems like a "bad" thing for a maintenance release. But I can't think of a reason why anyone would re-implement ITool or IToolChain. There are probably many users of the interface, but adding a new method doesn't break them (if I remember the Java binary compatibility rules correctly). Do we all agree with this?
Leo

(In reply to comment #7) > 1. Generally different options of one and the same tool might support different > path formats, on the other hand an ISV might want to supply one converter
I have given some thouhgt to this. The cleanest alternative in one way would be to specify the converter per option and change the interface of IOption. On the other hand it would be a waste because most options are not concerned with paths but rather with boolean or string values which don't need conversion.
So all in all the best alternative seems to remain to get the converter from the tool, but to make the interface so that the converter can decide for each individual IOption instance which (if any) conversion it will apply.
> interface to IOptionPathConverter. NOTE: there is a similar mechanism already > available for environment paths (see > org.eclipse.cdt.managedbuilder.core.IBuildPathResolver). We might also think > about defining one common mechanism, although Im OK with keeping
The problem that the two are solving is related, but from the way the IBuildPathResover is nested into the definition of the envVarBuildPath it seems difficult now to come up with a unified solution for the schema of the buildDefinitions. It is still up to a clever implementor to reuse much of the conversion code, maybe let one class implement both interfaces and point to it from the definitions of both the build path resolver and the path converter.
> IOptionPathConverter and IBuildPathResolver mechanisms separate since > IOptionPathConverter also includes the logic of dealing with path separators, > while IOptionPathConverter should only translate paths.
The above remark was not quite clear - comparing IOptionPathConverter to IOptionPathConverter.
So my judgment is that on the whole the implementation is good enough as it is. An even cleaner solution would require a redesign also of the envVarBuildPath schema.

(In reply to comment #10) Hi Leo,
> Interface breakage seems like a "bad" thing for a maintenance release. But I > can't think of a reason why anyone would re-implement ITool or IToolChain. > There are probably many users of the interface, but adding a new method doesn't > break them (if I remember the Java binary compatibility rules correctly). Do > we all agree with this? My understanding is that all buildDefinitions interfaces (ITool, IToolChain, IConfiguration, etc.) are "not intended to be implemented by clients", so extending those interfaces should work OK. So I would not call it "interface breakage". As far as I remember we did some interface extensions in the previous maintenance releases and did not have any problems with that.
Mikhail
I have no strong objectives as long as any new fields in the extension point schema are optional and no conversion is required.

(In reply to comment #13) > I have no strong objectives as long as any new fields in the extension point > schema are optional and no conversion is required.

bug.short_desc: Performance - Bundle.loadClass is too expensive

long_desc.thetext:
Repeated calls to org.osgi.framework.Bundle.loadClass are too expensive. Performance analysis of the call suggests that, due to the classloader delegation model that is employed, a number of unecessary class load attempts are made prior to the class being found in the cache. This causes performance problems with distributed applications that are running on top of the OSGi framework and are repeatedly sending serialized objects between JVMs.
From discussion with Tom Watson I understand that the delegation model used by the bundle class loader is parent -> cache -> disk. The suggestion made during the discussion was to change the delegation model to search the local cache first.

cache -> parent -> disk may also present problems with correct behavior when a dynamic import is wired since the dynamic import must start to mask the local version if there is a namespace conflict. Since there is no way to clear the cache, care must be taken to preserve proper bahavior.
What is the real issue with alway asking parent first? Is it the creation and throwing of ClassNotFoundExceptions when the parent does not have the class? The OSGi delegation model should limit the number of classloaders searched for a class since a delegation will only occur when the class comes from an imported package or one of the packages delegated to the bootclassloader. Use of Require-Bundle or setting the bootclasspath delegation to * will degrade performance since more classloader may need to be consulted to locate any given class.

cache -> parent -> disk also has other issues ...
- It will allow classes loaded while activating a lazy-start bundle to be loaded by another thread before the bundle has finished activation. This is because we will short circut the code that pays attention to whether the lazy-start bundle is active or not before returning the cached class. We could move the preFindLocalClass class loader hooks up to before the first cache lookup, but that move has other issues ...
- It will force us to ask the cache twice for first time class loads. This is because a classloader must make the calls to findLoadedClass and defineClass atomic; otherwise we risk defining a class more than once. So this change would result in a cache -> parent(OSGi) -> cache -> disk. This may have other performance issues by introducing another cache search.

(In reply to comment #1) > What is the real issue with alway asking parent first?
Running on an IBM j9 JVM the performance data showed java.util.zip.ZipFile.getEntry running hot when shared classes were disabled and com.ibm.oti.shared.SharedClassURLClasspathHelperImpl.findSharedClassImpl running hot with shared classes enabled. My understanding is that this is a result of the two parent classloaders going to disk in search of the class before it's found in the local cache.

(In reply to comment #3) > (In reply to comment #1) > > What is the real issue with alway asking parent first? > > Running on an IBM j9 JVM the performance data showed
Does the same problem exist on other JREs? Are you using the Sun java.util.zip implementation or the J9 impl? The J9 impl of zip was not very performant some years back when I looked at it.
I would like to see this documented as a problem across most popular JREs before we consider potentialy dangerous changes to optimize.

> Does the same problem exist on other JREs?
The problem's been observed on both Windows and Linux, unforunately with an IBM J9 VM in both cases. I am not sure that singling out the Zip implementation as the cause is correct. With shared classes enabled the method which looks in the cache runs hot; I believe it's the fact that so many class load attempts are being made rather than the repository from which the classes are being loaded (zip file or shared classes cache) which is the problem.

The information here is still too anecdotal to suggest a specific change. It has only been observed on J9 and not on other JREs. I think more detailed information is still required along with information which suggests the problems exists in other JREs.

Have you tried turning off the boot delegation? Tom experiemented with this recently and found in normal cases that it improved startup significantly. We would like to do this for real in 3.3 but have to consider all the implications. If you try and it and it helps, that will be more support for moving forward on it. Setting org.osgi.framework.bootdelegation= (to nothing) in the config.ini should do the trick.
Closing as fixed in M4 because we disabled boot delegation in bug 162231.
